+and it's handled automatically by the RTK base API. Non-RTK-API calls may need
+to add the header.
 
-- **Important (1):** Never do *initial* access control checks in hooks or
+- **Important (1):** If doing custom access checks (without the hasCapabilities
+  component or hook), never do *initial* access control checks in hooks or
   useEffects, and don't store the results in state. Doing so will lead to extra
-  renders and undesirable flashes of content. With `<HasAccess />` you get
-  exactly 1 check on component mount and no more. The result is memoized, so
-  it's truly only 1 check until the component is unmounted or a memoization
-  dependency changes (unlikely). All custom checks should behave the same way
-  (use the roles definied in the user.current slice).
+  renders and undesirable flashes of content. With `<HasCapabilities />` or
+  `useHasCapabilities()` you get exactly 1 check on component mount and no more.
+  The result is memoized, so it's truly only 1 check until the component is
+  unmounted or a memoization dependency changes (unlikely). All custom checks
+  should behave the same way (use the roles definied in the user.current slice).
 - **Important (2):** When adding capability checks to the UI library, remember
   that components will crash if used in an app *without* a user context and a
   Media Server connection. So, don't do any access control checks in components
